        "summaryHtml": "<p><a id=\"_Hlk208145443\"></a><strong>One Up On Wall Street How To Use What You Already Know To Make Money In The Market</strong></p><p><strong>Peter Lynch</strong></p><p>Year: 2000<br />Publisher: W. W. Norton & Company</p><p>Pages: 432</p><p><strong><br />About</strong></p><p>This book explains how everyday observations and common sense can be turned into profitable investment opportunities by identifying undervalued companies early.</p><p><strong>Product Description</strong></p><p>More than one million copies have been sold of this seminal book on investing in which legendary mutual-fund manager Peter Lynch explains the advantages that average investors have over professionals and how they can use these advantages to achieve financial success.<br /><br />America’s most successful money manager tells how average investors can beat the pros by using what they know. According to Lynch, investment opportunities are everywhere. From the supermarket to the workplace, we encounter products and services all day long. By paying attention to the best ones, we can find companies in which to invest before the professional analysts discover them. When investors get in early, they can find the “tenbaggers,” the stocks that appreciate tenfold from the initial investment. A few tenbaggers will turn an average stock portfolio into a star performer. </p><p>Lynch offers easy-to-follow advice for sorting out the long shots from the no-shots by reviewing a company’s financial statements and knowing which numbers really count. He offers guidelines for investing in cyclical, turnaround, and fast-growing companies.  As long as you invest for the long term, Lynch says, your portfolio can reward you. This timeless advice has made One Up on Wall Street a #1 bestseller and a classic book of investment know-how.</p><p><strong>Selective Summary</strong></p><p>In One Up on Wall Street, Peter Lynch demonstrates how ordinary investors can outperform professionals by leveraging personal knowledge and everyday experiences. Lynch explains that by paying attention to the products, services, and companies encountered in daily life, individuals can often spot promising businesses before Wall Street analysts recognize their potential. He categorizes stocks into six types—such as stalwarts, fast growers, and cyclicals—giving readers a framework for evaluating opportunities.</p><p>Lynch underscores the value of thorough research, urging investors to understand a company’s financial health, competitive advantage, and long-term prospects before buying shares. He cautions against blindly following trends and warns of common pitfalls such as overconfidence, chasing hot stocks, or ignoring debt levels.</p><p>The book emphasizes patience as a key ingredient for success, advising readers to hold on to fundamentally strong companies long enough for their value to be realized. Lynch’s approach empowers individuals to rely less on market forecasts and more on rational, research-driven decision-making.</p><p><strong>Book Reviews</strong></p><p>Rating: 4.6 | (12,186)</p><p>Top comments: </p><p>1. “Excellent info” – Sud Pillay</p><p>2. “I dont know how many times I giggled while reading this book. Lynch has this uncanny ability to make his writing pleasant to read and dishing out gold bites at the same time” –  Anton</p><p>3. “Good book” –  Finsko</p><p>4. “If you are into investing and need to read something that helps you understand where to invest. this is the book for you. in simple terms the author advises on what to look for when investing your money. DISCLAIMER: this is not a financial advice.” –  DolaBhai</p><p>5. “Excellent book, must have for investors, I may have to read it a couple of times for info to sink in.” –  Geoff Ryan</p><p><strong>Indicative Price: $ 29.27</strong></p><p><strong>BUY NOW</strong></p>"
